<! Meteo Station [2013] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_odd">

					<div id="meteo_station">
							<header>
								<h2>Meteo Station [2013]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Basics</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									The idea behind building a homemade Meteorological Station (or something near this concept), came, as strange as it may seem, from the need to learn python scripting for professional purposes.
									To do so I intended to invest some free time on a homemade project using the versatile Raspberry Pi (which I already introduced <a href="#RPi">here</a>).
								</p>
								
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/meteo.jpg" data-lightbox="image-a">
										<img src="images/meteo.jpg" height="300" style="float:left; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								
								<p>
									To accompany my Raspberry I looked around my electronics box, where I found (amongst other things): a temperature sensor, a couple of PIC16F819, two matched RF Transceivers and a shiny breadboard.
									With these components in hand, there wasn't much choice on what to do: I was going to create a Meteorological Station (or at least for now, a "basic digital thermometer")!
								</p>
								
								<p>
									So, about the Python scripting, where does it fit exatly? 
								</p>
								<p>
									Okay, the Python script is suposed to be running on the Raspberry, where it must receive and interpret the information of the temperature sensor, then making it available for display on a personal website.
									But let's not get ahead of ourselves!
								</p>
								<p>
									Below I will explain the project in further detail, for that dividing it in 3 parts: the <b>Reading Station</b>; the <b>Link to the Internet</b>; and the <b>Displaying Website</b>.
								</p>
								
								<br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Reading Station</strong></li>
								</ul>
								
								
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/pic16f.jpg" data-lightbox="image-a">
										<img src="images/pic16f.jpg" height="300" style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>
									This 1st part of the system, where the temperature is sensed, is supposed to be a standalone module powered by a battery and so, completely portable (up to a certain radius distance from the Raspberry Pi).
								</p>
								<p>
									It's main components are:
								</p>
								
									<ul><ul>
										<li><b> 
											<a href="http://www.analog.com/static/imported-files/data_sheets/TMP35_36_37.pdf" class="link">TMP37:</a></b> 
											a simple low voltage temperature sensor from <a href="http://www.analog.com/" class="link">Analog</a>. 
											This sensor is intended for applications over the range of 5 C to 100 C and provides an output scale factor of 20 mV/C.
										</li>
										<li><b>
											<a href="http://ww1.microchip.com/downloads/en/DeviceDoc/39598F.pdf" class="link">PIC16F189:</a></b> 
											a generic purpose Microcontroller from <a href="http://www.microchip.com/" class="link">Microchip</a>, with the essential features (for this project) of Analog-to-Digital conversion and UART interfacing; 
										</li>
										<li><b>
											<a href="http://www.sureelectronics.net/goods.php?id=1053" class="link">Wireless RF Transceiver:</a></b> 
											a 2 pieces RF Transceiver with an UART interface, for establishing the communication between the serial interfaces of the PIC16F819 and the Raspberry Pi.</b>
										</li>					
									</ul></ul>
								<p>	
									As of the configuration setup it is very simple: a basic C program (compiled with <a href="http://http://www.ccsinfo.com/" class="link">CCS:</a>) was loaded into the PIC, so as to read the TMP37 output voltage with the internal ADC.
									This C program is then responsible to send the raw information (hexadecimal format from 0x00 to 0xFF) throught the serial interface to the PIC RF module which forwards it to its twin module, on the Raspberry side.
								</p>
								<br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Link to the Internet</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									The information emmited above is then received by the Raspberry Pi, using its RF Module connected to the serial interface.
									A Python script transforms the hexadecimal information gathered into both Voltage and Temperature using the formulas:
								</p>
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9632 <b>Voltage</b> = Raw/255 * 5 V;</li>
										<li>&#9632 <b>Temperature</b> = Voltage * 50 C;</li>
									</ul></ul>
																		
								<p>
									The reason to process the information at this side of the link instead of the PIC's side, is that this simplifies the information transmission (only the raw signal is sent). 
									Furthermore the purpose of the whole project was to improve the Python scripting skills, and not so much the C programming, so it was only logical to perform these operations on the receiving side of the transmission.
								</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rasp_rf.jpg" data-lightbox="image-a">
										<img src="images/rasp_rf.jpg" width="400" style="margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>
									With the data of interest at hand, the same script then uploads the freshly read temperature to an online SQL database.
									This last step meaning the information of interest is now available online, and the process almost finished.
								</p>
								<p>
									A note still for the fact that the refered script is placed at the Raspberry <b>rc.local</b>, so as to be started after the boot, thus updating the database every time the device is powered up.
								</p>

								<br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Displaying Website</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									The final piece of the puzzle is the website where the temperature is finally displayed. 
									Here a php script running on a webserver, accesses the same SQL database that is linked to the Raspberry, and downloads the latest temperature.
									This value is then printed on the display inside a circle which has different colors for distinct temperatures:
								</p>
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9632 <b style="color: blue;">Blue:</b> temperature is less than 10 C;</li>
										<li>&#9632 <b style="color: green;">Green:</b> temperature is in between 10 C and 20 C;</li>
										<li>&#9632 <b style="color: orange;">Orange:</b> temperature is in between 20 C and 30 C;</li>
										<li>&#9632 <b style="color: red;">Red:</b> temperature is higher than 30 C;</li>
									</ul></ul>									
								<p>
									The aforementioned website, which is public and available at <a href="http://meteo.comuv.com/">http://meteo.comuv.com/</a> is quite straightforward and effective in filling its only purpose (for now at least): showing the current temperature of the room where the Reading Station is located at.
									A picture of this website main page is found below.
								</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/meteo_web.png" data-lightbox="image-a">
										<img src="images/meteo_web.png" width="700" style="margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
	
	
								<br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>To be Continued</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									So, the first part of the project is finished with success, but it isn't all!
									Further improvements can be expected in the near future:
									
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9632 <b>Specific voltage reference:</b> for improving the measurements accuracy;</li>
										<li>&#9632 <b>Some batteries:</b> replacing the USB power connection will improve the system versatility;</li>
										<li>&#9632 <b>More/Different sensors:</b> carbon monoxide gas sensor, gas sensor, relative humidity sensor, the hypotheses are endless;</li>
										<li>&#9632 <b>New PCB:</b> instead of a breadboard, the final system should have a good looking PCB, with the components soldered;</li>
										<li>&#9632 <b>Custom Case:</b> for a final product look, a case will be made to protect the PCB and the whole Reading System.</li>
									</ul></ul>			
														
								</p>
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>

				
					
				
<! eMenu Service [2013] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_even">

					<div id="emenu_service">
							<header>
								<h2>eMenu Service [2013]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<ul>
									<li><strong>A new Service</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rest.png" data-lightbox="image-b">
										<img src="images/rest.png" height="250" style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>
									eMenu is a brand new service, that includes both a platform for restaurants to insert information related with their activity, but also a mobile application where their clients can consult this information.
								</p>
								<p>
									This idea followed the development and publication of <a id="inside_links" href="#CantSiemens">Cantina Siemens</a>, when a friend suggested the purpose of this application to be more encompassing, not only as an application for viewing the canteen's menu at my workplace but with a broader purpose.
									Although  at the time the suggestion was not taken very seriously, since no further changes were made to <a href="#CantSiemens">Cantina Siemens</a>, the idea had been planted. 
								</p>
								<p>
									The concept was embraced afterwards, with this new project being born from the will to create something new. Some (many) elements were taken from the experience with the canteen application but many others were added/improved or completely changed.	
								</p>	
								<p>
									But first and foremost, let's go through some main points of this project, by enlightening the two main perspectives:
								</p>	
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Restaurants:</b>
											<ul>
												<li>&#9632 Pay for a membership account that allows them to use the web platform;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Insert their information (plates, menu's, prices, locations, ...) on the platform;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Get their data placed on a shared database with other restaurants;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Gain a simple, easy and quick way to get closer to their clients;</li>
											</ul></li>
											
										<li>&#9658 <b>Clients:</b>
											<ul>
												<li>&#9632 Can download the eMenu application for free;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Have a single point of access to all the establishments on the database;</li>
												<li>&#9632 Get an innovative service, with vast information on their favourite restaurants;</li>
											</ul></li><br>
											
									</ul></ul>	
									
								<p>
									Restaurants and their clients are brought together with this service, the restaurants without having to spend lots of money on advertising, the clients without having to resort to different points to get the information they want.	
								</p>
									
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/emenu_c.png" data-lightbox="image-b">
										<img src="images/emenu_c.png" height="300" style="border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								
								<br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Web Platform</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									Having made the introductions, it is time to go into details. 
									It should be noted that for the time being only the web platform will be described since the other half of this service, the customer's Android application is still on a development phase.
								</p>

								<p>
									So, accessing the website for the first time, the welcoming page is displayed, together with a menu containing the options to access the list of restaurants, the login or the join form page. 
									A user having successfully made the registration on the service, can, after login, access one of the following pages:
								</p>
								
								
								<p>	
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Menu ('Ementa')</b>: here the different plates available are shown (amongst them the Meat Plates, Drinks or Deserts);</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Restaurant Information ('Name')</b>: some information on the place, such as telephone, location or description;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Restaurant Account ('Conta')</b>: page for editing the information above;</li>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Logout ('Terminar Sessão')</b>: option to logout, and return to the welcoming page.</li>
									</ul></ul>	
								</p>
								<br>

								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/emenu_e.png" data-lightbox="image-b">
										<img src="images/emenu_e.png" height="250" style="border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>
									A feature that must be highlighted is that the access to the member's area is completely secure, since an encrypted password is enforced.
									This way, only the restaurant can edit its own details.
								</p>
								<p>
									As introduced before there is also the option to check the restaurants on the database and respective menu's and details, however this is to be used on a client's perspective, so a logout is necessary from the member´s area.
								</p>

								<br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Wrap up</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									The foundations are made, and the web interface is now ready to be used. 
									The next step should be terminating the application for which the first steps have already been taken a couple of months ago with <a href="#CantSiemens">Cantina Siemens</a>.
								</p>
								<p>
										In the meantime the website is now available for the most curious ones  (by clicking the image below), and the <a href="mailto:luisfiliperdias@gmail.com">Inbox</a> ready to receive suggestions and hints!
								</p>
		
									<p style="text-align:centre;">
										<a href="http://emenu.uphero.com/">
											<img src="images/emenu_f.png"  id="googleLink" height="100" style="border-radius:10px;"/>
										</a>
									</p>
								
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>

				
					
<! Horarios Vimeca [2013] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_odd">

					<div id="horarios_vimeca">
							<header>
								<h2>Horarios Vimeca [2013]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Context</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/vimeca.jpg" data-lightbox="image-0">
										<img src="images/vimeca.jpg" height="250"  style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>
									Horarios Vimeca was the second experience over which I engaged the Android world. 
								</p>
								<p>
									As a customer of the <a title="Vimeca Website" class="link" href="http://www.vimeca.pt">Vimeca</a>'s Bus company for over half a year, I noticed a deficit of information on the Bus timings.
									No digital information panel, not even the printed timetables posted on the Bus stop. 
									This meant inability to know the arrival times of the different Bus.
								</p>

								<p>
									Room for a new service emerged, room to improve the <a title="Vimeca Website" class="link" href="http://www.vimeca.pt">Vimeca</a> client's satisfaction and convenience: an application for checking the Bus timetables at any time, any place, at the customer's Android device.	
								</p>
								<ul>
									<br>
									<li><strong>Development</strong></li>
								</ul>
																		
								<p>
									As of the development time for this application, whilst significantly more complex than <a href="#CantSiemens">Cantina Siemens</a>, the time was much smaller.
									This is explained with the learning curve obtained from the previous experience, meaning some entry barriers had been lifted, and things made easier.
									As an example of this time/difficulty difference, the number of versions: <b>21</b> for <a href="#CantSiemens">Cantina Siemens</a> vs. <b>4</b> for Horarios Vimeca.
								</p>
										
								<p>
									Similarly to the other app, the information is also gathered online, in this case from <a title="Vimeca Website" class="link" href="http://www.vimeca.pt">Vimeca</a>'s website (<a title="Vimeca Website" class="link" href="www.vimeca.pt">www.vimeca.pt</a>) where all the timetables and routes are available, and is then integrated into the application for a simple and intuitive inquiry.
								</p>

								<ul>
									<br>
									<li><strong>Showcase</strong></li>
								</ul>
									
									
								<p>
									Getting into further details over this App, and relying on the screenshots below we have that: the first view displayed is the loading menu, where the selected bus timetable is loaded in the background.						
									Then the main view is displayed, and organized as follows:
								</p>
									<ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Selected Bus ('Autocarro')</b>: list to select which Bus schedules are to be displayed;</li><br>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Origin of the departure ('Origem')</b>: the direction from which to display the schedules;</li><br>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Departure hour ('Hora de partida')</b>: a filter applied to the timetable, to simplify the search of the desired hour;</li><br>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Route ('Percurso')</b>: loads the route image on a new view, for display on the device;</li><br>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Circulation days ('Sem', 'Sab', Dom')</b>: days of circulation and respective schedules divided in: Weekdays ('Sem'), Saturday ('Sab') and Sunday ('Dom');</li><br>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Selected Departure</b>: selected origin of departure;</li><br>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Bus Origin departures</b>: main feature, list with the departing hour from the origin of the course. To get the hours for the intermediate stops, the Route option must be used.</li><br>
										<li>&#9658 <b>Additional Information ('Clique para obter...)'</b>: pop-up with any additional information available at the website.</li><br>
									</ul></ul>
									
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/vimeca.png" data-lightbox="image-0">
										<img src="images/vimeca.png" width="600"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>
									Although internet access is required on the first use of this application, so as to load the required Bus information, this information is then stored in a SQLite database on the device.
								</p>
								<p>
									This means that the information on the timetable becomes available even for offline access.
									Offline access was viewed as an indispensable feature since the beginning of the development, given that internet access at the Bus stops is scarce, and lacking it would frustrate the purpose.
								</p>
							
								<p>
									Similarly to <a href="#CantSiemens">Cantina Siemens</a> this application is also available for Android at Google Play, for free.
								To try it out, just download it from the image below.
								</p>
								
					
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="http://goo.gl/Fylpam">
										<img src="images/google.png" id="googleLink" width="500"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								
							</p>
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
