<! Raspberry Experiences [2012] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_odd">

					<div id="raspberry_experiences">
							<header>
								<h2>Raspberry Experiences [2012]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rpi_1.jpg" data-lightbox="image-2">
										<img src="images/rpi_1.jpg" height="250"  style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<ul>	
									<li><strong>Raspwho?</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>The Raspberry Pi is a very small single-board computer developed in the UK with teaching purposes but whose potential has facilitated its deployment as a very powerful tool for both homemade projects and some companies.</p>
								<p>The possibility to have a computer for $40, running a Linux OS, connected to the internet, and having directly available for example an UART, an I2C module or a dozen of GPIO pins, is very attractive.</p>
								<p>Following this trend, and having seen some interesting projects over the internet I decided to invest in one of these devices, mostly for its versatility.</p>
								<ul>
								<br>
								<li><strong>SSH Remote Control</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>One of the first thing I made was registering a dynamic DNS service, so I could gain remote access to the Raspberry (connected to the web via the Ethernet port). Having done this I also enabled on my router the NAT service, where I mapped the SSH Port of my $40 computer to a public Port. This way I became capable to enter the device&#8217;s terminal from any place of the web, and thus configure it. Even though an LCD could be connected via HDMI port, as well as a keyboard and a mouse turning this low-cost PC into a &#8220;normal&#8221; computer, I&#8217;ve chosen to access it from my PC with SSH, allowing a more comfortable operation.</p>
								<ul>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rpi_2.jpg" data-lightbox="image-2">
										<img src="images/rpi_2.jpg" height="200" style="float:left; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<br>
								<li><strong>FTP Server</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>As a second step, I configured an FTP server running as a daemon, and then plugged an  USB Flash Drive on the Raspberry Pi, so I could share files between all the computers on my network, and store them on only one location. Furthermore I mapped both FTP Ports on the router with NAT, and so I gained access to these files from any remote place. In a near future I&#8217;m considering replacing the USB Flash Drive with an 1 TB HD Drive using a Hub (since it draws a lot of current), thus creating a spot on the network where I can access all my data.</p>
								<ul>
								<br>
								<li><strong>Transmission Remote<br /></strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>Another configuration I made, towards a more integrated/practical IT environment at my place, was configuring a Torrent client (namely Transmission), running as daemon, associated to the corresponding  remote access service. Then I added a remote transmission widget on my browser, and opened the ports on the router, et voilà, I was now able to add/remove/manage any legal torrent/magnet from any place, with the great commodity of arriving home with the contents already downloaded and available for use.</p>
								<ul>
								<br>
								<li><strong>Receipt Management Software</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>Although the utility of all the previous configurations, the most interesting thing I made so far with the Raspberry Pi was to develop a simple C routine to run on the raspberry or any device accessing with an SSH session.</p>
								<p>This consisted in a Receipt Management SW, where I could save, add, list or organize different receipts very easily, instead of using an ordinary receipt book. This program which would run by simply executing a bin file on the Raspberry Pi terminal, had the information saved in the USB Flash Drive so it could be easy to transport and hard get lost.</p>
								<p>As of the program itself, it had the following interface:</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rpi_4.png" data-lightbox="image-2">
										<img src="images/rpi_4.png" height="280"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>Here, if you selected the 2nd option, for instance, you would have a list of the available plates, and then the details of the specified one:</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rpi_5.png" data-lightbox="image-2">
										<img src="images/rpi_5.png" height="310"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>Even thought this was a relatively easy to implement application, it was very fun to do, and it has been proven very useful (especially in those days when you don't know what to do for dinner!)</p>
								<ul>
								<br>
								<li><strong>General Overview</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>At the end of these experiences a lot of advantages of this &#8220;cheap&#8221; computer seem obvious: it can perform most of  the same operations as an ordinary computer, while consuming much less resources, it&#8217;s very light and portable, provides very easy access to low-level components  it can be easily remotely accessed (with a smartphone inclusively).</p>
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>

<! Micro-Mouse II [2012] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_even">

					<div id="micro_mouse_ii">
							<header>
								<h2>Micro-Mouse II [2012]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								
								<a href="images/rato0.jpg" data-lightbox="image-3">
									<img src="images/rato0.jpg" height="250" style="float:right; margin: 0 1% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px"/>
								</a>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Motivation</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									As a second attempt on the Micro-Mouse competition title, after achieving the 2nd place in the previous year (<a href="#MicroMouse" class="link">Micro-Mouse 2011</a>),
								me and <a title="Fábio Rico's Website" class="link" href="http://www.fabiorvrico.wordpress.com">Fábio Rico</a>, decided to participate again.
								</p>
								<p>
									This time, however, a decision was made to go farther, to increase the challenge, so we settled to build the entire robot from scratch, and only then add some intelligence to it (software).
								This made the task at hands way harder, but also much more amusing and challenging. 
								</p>
								<p>
									An early sketch can be found on the picture to the right.
								</p>
								<br>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Development</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
								<p>
									We started out with the idea: "Let's create a tank-like robot!". 
								</p>
								<p>
									We assembled some bicycle chains (to create robot caterpillar tracks), a thin base of metal for the structure, pieces of wood to fasten the sensors and create some wheels, acrylic for the Lighthouse receiver pole and then we bought all the electronics required and got down to work.
								</p>
								<p>
									The intellectual process began, and the pros and cons of the raw ideas had to be discussed. 
									As an example of this was the drop of the caterpillar tracks, which, after some tests revealed themselves "too heavy" and unpractical - our small motors weren't able to move them fast enough.
									Simple wheels, made of simple wood were adopted instead.
								</p>
								<a href="images/rato3.jpg" data-lightbox="image-3">
									<img src="images/rato3.jpg" height="250" style="float:left; margin: 0 5% 1% 1%; border-radius:10px"/>
								</a>
								<p>
									The will to make a "tank-like" robot remained however, so we added a cannon to keep the idea alive, on whose top stood the beacon signal receiver, and would rise from an initial horizontal position to a vertical position at the beginning of the contest, with the help of a servo motor.
									Another servo was connected to the beacon receiver, allowing a 180 degrees movement, for an increased probability of capturing the signal.
								</p>
								<p>
									Apart from these design characteristics, the vehicle was controlled with the pic32 evaluation board won at the previous competition, and had some of the following components:
								<ul>
									<ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul><ul>
										<li>&#9658 1* Ground Sensors: <a href="http://www.vishay.com/docs/83760/tcrt5000.pdf" class="link">TCRT5000</a> from <a href="http://www.vishay.com/" class="link">Vishay</a>;</li>
										<li>&#9658 2* Obstacle Sensor: <a href="https://www.sparkfun.com/datasheets/Components/GP2Y0A21YK.pdf" class="link">GP2Y0A21YK</a> from <a href="http://sharp-world.com/" class="link">Sharp</a>;</li>
										<li>&#9658 1* Infrared Receiver: <a href="http://www.farnell.com/datasheets/9749.pdf" class="link">HIM602</a> from <a href="http://www.apc-hero.co.uk/" class="link">Hero</a>;</li>
										<li>&#9658 2* DC Motors: 12V with 20RPM;</li>
										<li>&#9658 2* Servo Motors: TBD;</li>
									</ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul>
								</ul>
								</p>
								<p>
									More specifically on the pic32 board, a special shield was made, so as to simplify the interconnection with the rest of the components.
								This board, which was completely made at home, using the Laser Printer - Iron - Ferric Chloride Solution method, can be seen in the picture to the left, and has the following characteristics:
								</p>
								<a href="images/rato2.jpg" data-lightbox="image-3">
									<img src="images/rato2.jpg" height="350" style="float:right; margin: 0 1% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px"/>
								</a>	
								<ul>
									<ul>
										<li>&#9658 Hot-pluggable socket for the pic32 development board;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Signal conditioning for the all the DC motors, servos and sensors provided on-board;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Some on-board buttons and LEDs available for testing;</li>
										<li>&#9658 Hot-pluggable slot for an RF UART module provided, for remote control of the vehicle (non-competition add-on);</li>
										<li>&#9658 Output/input ports available for future usage as a generic tests board.</li>
									</ul>
								</ul>
								<p>
									With all the hardware assembled, all that was left was to create the code, the brain of the robot.
									For this, part of the previous year robot intelligence was reutilized, however many aspects had to be optimized/modified or completely renovated due to the new hardware.
									This was another challenge, but it was exciting to see the robot coming to life, every time we added new functions to the pic32.
								</p>
								<p>
									As of the final product, dressed for the competition it is pictured to the right, on its full splendour as a small tank-like vehicle!
								</p>													
								<ul>
									<li><strong>The Competition</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									After the robot was assembled the tests phase began, which took some time due to the constant modifications made to improve the overall performance.
								One of these sessions can be seen in the video below, where the robot had to avoid the obstacles around it, whilst not having a destination reference.
								</p>
								<br>
								<span class='embed-youtube' style='text-align:centre; display: block;'>
									<iframe width='100%' height='500' src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/D5OZdfUp0_E" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
								</span>
								<br>
																
								<p>
									Although in the latter training sessions before the competition, and in the competition training grounds themselves the robot had a rather positive performance, during the real thing, something else happened.
								A problem related with the ground sensors (used for beacon area detection) happened: they were receiving the signals emitted from the contestant's obstacle detectors, and interpreting that as an indication of "arrival at destination". 
								That meant a faulty behaviour, immediately after the start of the competition, and consequent declassification from the match.
								</p>
								<p>
									During the second round of the competition, efforts were made to solve this problem, but with no success. In the end the robot was declassified from both rounds, leaving only frustration from the fact that the robot could execute the course with success, but only if it was alone on the field.
								</p>
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Conclusion</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>
									Although no trophy was won, and the attempt on the title had failed, it was still a very rewarding experience to have built the Micro-Mouse from scratch, which separated us from the competition, who chose to develop the software for provided robots.
								</p>
								<p>
									This can be confirmed from the picture below, were our robot, BEST-A (which in Portuguese stands for Beast), poses for a photo together with its clearly distinct (but equal amongst themselves) contenders.
								</p>
								
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rato1.jpg" data-lightbox="image-3">
										<img src="images/rato1.jpg" height="350" style="float:centre; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px"/>
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>
									What remains in the end nevertheless, was not the dread performance on the tournament, but the knowledge applied and acquired during this great adventure.
								Most of all, it was an opportunity to apply different competences acquired during many courses, to put together many valences (from programming, to signal conditioning or even control theory) into building something concrete, with defined objectives and purposes.
								</p>
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>


<! Illumination No-Cost [2012] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_odd">

					<div id="illumination_no_cost">
							<header>
								<h2>Illumination No-Cost [2012]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<ul>					
								<a href="images/rf_1.png" data-lightbox="image-4">
									<img src="images/rf_1.png" height="300" style="float:right; margin: 0 5% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px"/>
								</a>
								<li><strong>The "What?"</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>This project is related with the work I made for my master thesis, and is involved with the concept of Energy Harvesting and the means to transform the received energy into a useful application, in this case, generating light.</p>
								<p>This work was made in cooperation with the Telecommunications Institute of Aveiro, under the orientation of Professor Dr. Nuno Borges Carvalho, to whom I&#8217;m grateful for the support provided.</p>
								<p>Basically the idea here was, through the understanding of the non-linear processes involved in the rectification process that converts the ambient RF power into DC energy, creating systems with high efficiency and/or output voltage. This ought to be achieved from the waves emitted by an ordinary FM emitter antenna, allowing the powering of 2/3 low consumption LED&#8217;s from a couple of hundred meters of distance to the source.</p>
								<ul>
								<br>
								<li><strong>The "How?"</strong></li>
								</ul>

								<p>Since the maximum harvested energy from the receiver antenna is always limited, and it's very hard to increase at about 100 MHz specially (only developing agglomerates or very large or  of antennas) a very delicate design of the circuit that effectively converts the RF energy from the waves into the DC is required. So it was the main point of this work to develop methods for increasing the efficiency of this process. A special focus was given to the matching of the conversion circuit, since a careful analysis revealed that the reflected power consisted in the major percentage of the power loss.</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rf_2.png" data-lightbox="image-4">
										<img src="images/rf_2.png" style="border-radius:10px; margin:1%;" width="474" height="294" />
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>That said, without entering an extensive level of detail, one of the main tools developed was a software running on ADS 2012, that allowing a flexible and accurate matching of the circuit. This tool allowed to match the circuit considering either for a specific output voltage or for a higher power efficiency. A picture of this can be found above, where it&#8217;s seen the smith charts used for the matching on both purposes (power efficiency and output voltage) on the centre and a series of auxiliary equations on the side. Also the results for each of the matching circles (and in the limit the red point), show the current values for those positions.<br />
								Applying this theory a couple of circuits were developed, some to achieve higher efficiency using only one diode as main rectifier, and other employed more complex rectifiers/voltage multipliers such as the Dickson or the Villard to attain output voltages as high as possible. In parallel a simple FM antenna was built for proof of concept purposes. Some of the circuits developed can be found on the pictures below.</p>
 								<p style="text-align:centre;">
 									<a href="images/rf_3.jpg" data-lightbox="image-4">
										<img src="images/rf_3.jpg" style="border-radius:10px; margin:1%;" height="180"  />
									</a>
								</p>
								<ul>
								<br>
								<li><strong>The "Big Picture"</strong></li>
								</ul>
								<p>Getting all the elements together, a system that effectively converted the energy of a FM radio emitter into visible light was achieved, having been tested on the field in Aveiro, Portugal.</p>
								<p>Basically the experienced consisted in two phases:</p>
								<ul>
									<ul>
										<li><span style="line-height:13px;"><strong>a)</strong> The energy-harvesting circuits without LED&#8217;s were connected to the FM antenna on one side, and to a multimeter on the other to measure the harvested DC voltage.</span></li>
										<li><strong>b) </strong>The multimeter and the previous circuits were replaced with a different set of circuits with 1 or 2 LED&#8217;s, to verify if the harvested energy could generate light.</li>
									</ul>
								</ul>
								<p>Both these experiences are briefly presented on a short video, presented below, where an overview of the practical results of this work can be found</p>
								<span class='embed-youtube' style='text-align:centre; display: block;'>
									<iframe class='youtube-player' type='text/html' width='593' height='364' src='http://www.youtube.com/embed/xEHFZO_CSiU?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;fs=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;wmode=transparent' frameborder='0'></iframe>
								</span>
								<p>On the picture below , the best results achieved are again presented, where it can be seen that up to a distance of 400m from an emitter, 2 LEDs where successfully powered up, having been obtained about 5.34 V.</p>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/rf_4.png" data-lightbox="image-4">
										<img src="images/rf_4.png" style="border-radius:10px; margin:1%;" height="350px">								
									</a>
								</p>
								<p>Closer to the same antenna, with both LEDs also turned on, a voltage as high as 7.01 V was possible.</p>
								
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>

<! Micro-Mouse I [2011] --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
					<section id="portfolio" class="projects_even">
					<div id="micro_mouse_i">
							<header>
								<h2>Micro-Mouse I [2011]</h2>
							</header>
							<div id="text_format">
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/micro1.jpg" data-lightbox="image-5">
										<img src="images/micro1.jpg" style="float:left; margin: 1% 5% 1% 1%; border-radius:10px;"width="400">
									</a>
								</p>
								Micro-Mouse is an event where small robots compete against each other to solve maze as fastest and with the minimum collisions as possible.<br><br> 
								Basically the robots have to follow a signal until they reach a destination, and then they have to return to their starting point, and all has to be made without any human interference. An example of a (very simple) maze can be found below.<br><br>
								In March 2011, together with <a title="Fábio Rico" href="http://www.fabiorvrico.wordpress.com" class="link">Fábio Rico</a>, I decided to participate on the local contest of my university. This seemed a great opportunity to apply some of the knowledge acquired in some of the courses I attended. Although this was a multidisciplinary contest evolving both Hardware and Software competences, we chose (as did all the participants in that year&#8217;s contest) to
								borrow the hardware provided by the organization of the event and focus on the software to solve the maze, only.<br>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/micro2.jpg" data-lightbox="image-5">
										<img src="images/micro2.jpg"  style="float:right; margin: 1% 1% 1% 5%; border-radius:10px;" width="200">
									</a>
								</p>
								This robot, that came equipped with two DC motors and respective H-bridges, three Sharp distance sensors, an IV receiver (to detect the signal emitted from the centre of the maze) and a pic18f for processing, had to combine the abilities of following walls, avoiding other robots and finding the centre of the maze, all on it's own. As a student of the 4th year of Electronics and Telecommunications Engineering at the time, this seemed very fun and appealing challenge.
								To achieve the objective of building this &#8220;intelligent&#8221; being, we made use of the transparent reading and writing of the available HW modules, and applied this information into a couple of control algorithms to perform the following operations:<br><br>
								<ul>
									<li>&#9658 Follow Walls</li>
									<li>&#9658 Avoid Obstacles (Other robots, very near walls)</li>
									<li>&#9658 Follow Beacon (to reach the centre)</li>
									<li>&#9658 Avoid Beacon (after reaching the centre of the maze, our implemented solution to reach the starting point was to just get away from the centre for a specified amount of time and then stopping)</li>
								</ul>
								The developed code, which was compiled with CCS and then sent to a pic18f258 trough a TinyBootLoader application every time changes where made, followed a simple structure with functions for each of the operations it had to execute, and some interruptions to generate time-triggered events, and some reads from the ADC.<br><br>
								The robot itself, which is shown in the photo above, having made a very good contest on the first three rounds, applied to the finals where it managed the second place of the competition, what earned us a pic32 proprietary board from the University of Aveiro Electronics Department (picture below).<br><br>
								<p style="text-align:centre;">
									<a href="images/micro3.jpg" data-lightbox="image-5">
										<img src="images/micro3.jpg" style="border-radius:10px" width="500">
									</a>
								</p>
							</div>
						</div>
							<footer>
								<a href="#portfolio" class="button scrolly">Back to Projects</a>
							</footer>
					</section>
					
